 In C, you can terminate a program using the `exit()` function. This function can be called from any part of the code and it will immediately end the program.

Here is an example:
```
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    exit(0);
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the `exit()` function is called after the `printf()` statement, which means that the program will end immediately after printing "Hello, World!". The first argument passed to `exit()` is the status code, which is used by the operating system to determine how the program ended. In this case, a status code of 0 is used to indicate successful termination.

You can also terminate a program using the `return` statement, but this will only work if the program is being executed as the main function of a larger program. If the program is being run as a standalone program, it will not terminate properly if you use the `return` statement.

